<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-10-03T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-10-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="12" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d12">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">711.4112a/52</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the Ambassador in Great Britain (<persName type="from">Bingham</persName>)</hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#left">No. 101</seg>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-10-03">October 3,
                                        1933</date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Department refers to its
                                instruction No. 450 of July 28, 1930, to despatch No. 1158 of August
                                25, 1930, and to previous correspondence relating to the negotiation
                                of a proposed treaty of arbitration between the Government of the
                                United States of America and the Government of Great Britain,
                                extending the policy of arbitration enunciated in the convention
                                signed at Washington, April 4, 1908,<note n="17" xml:id="d12fn17">
                                    <ref target="frus1908#pg_382">
                                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1908, p.
                                    382</ref>.</note> which expired by limitation on June 4,
                                1928.</p>
                            <p>The Department desires the Embassy to ascertain informally whether
                                the Foreign Office has completed its preliminary consideration of
                                the draft treaty and is prepared to continue the negotiations.</p>
                            <p>Very truly yours,</p>
                            <closer>For the Secretary of State: <lb/>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">William Phillips</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>